---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Generator Size Calculator | What Size Generator Do I Need? | CalcForDIY"
  description="Calculate the exact size generator you need for your home. Select your essential appliances to instantly calculate your total running watts and starting surge wattage."
>

  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebApplication",
    "name": "Generator Size Calculator",
    "description": "Free generator sizing calculator that computes total running watts and maximum surge watts to recommend the perfect portable or standby generator size.",
    "applicationCategory": "CalculatorApplication",
    "operatingSystem": "Web Browser",
    "offers": { "@type": "Offer", "price": "0", "priceCurrency": "USD" }
  }
  </script>

  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between Running Watts and Starting Watts?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Running Watts (or Rated Watts) is the continuous power an appliance needs to stay on. Starting Watts (or Surge Watts) is the brief burst of extra power needed for a few seconds to start up an electric motor. Appliances with compressors or motors (like refrigerators, air conditioners, and well pumps) require surge watts. Appliances with heating elements (like space heaters or toasters) generally do not."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why don't I add all my starting watts together?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "You do not need to add all your surge watts together because you will not start every single appliance in your house at the exact same millisecond. To properly size a generator, you add up the Running Watts of everything you want to power, and then add the single highest Starting Wattage among those items. This ensures the generator can handle the base load plus the biggest possible spike."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I run my whole house on a portable generator?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "You can run most essential circuits on a large portable generator (7,500 to 10,000+ watts) if you have a manual transfer switch installed by an electrician. However, you likely will not be able to run high-draw appliances simultaneously—for example, you cannot run a Central AC and an Electric Oven at the same time on a portable generator. For true whole-house backup without load management, you need a large standby generator (18,000+ watts)."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>

